'''Hyman Irving Biegeleisen''' (June 4, 1904 – May 3, 1991<ref name="obit">{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CE5DC123CF93BA35756C0A967958260 |title=Dr. H. I. Biegeleisen, An Expert on Veins, 86 |date=1991-05-08 |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=2009-03-05}}</ref>) was an [[United States|American]] [[physician]] and pioneer of [[phlebology]]. In 1964, he founded the Phlebology Society of America (now incorporated into the [http://www.phlebology.org American College of Phlebology]). He was one of the first doctors in the United States to use injection as a method of treating [[varicose veins]], and coined the term ''[[sclerotherapy]]'' to describe the treatment.<ref name="obit"/>
==Education== Beigeleisen graduated from Stuyvesant High School and Columbia University and received a medical degree from Long Island College Hospital.
